RIYADH: Digital security company Elm will debut on Saudi Arabia’s main stock index, TASI, on Feb. 16, according to a bourse filing. Owned by the Public Investment Fund, the company had earlier raised $820 million in proceeds from an initial public offering. The listing comes amid a boom in the Saudi initial public offering market in a bid to enhance liquidity, especially after leading the Gulf in 2021 with record offerings, by companies including ACWA Power and stc. The final offer price was set at SR128 ($34.1) per share, the top end of an indicative range. Based in Riyadh, Elm provides secure e-business services and information technology solutions to private and public sector businesses in the Kingdom. 